<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="398" pageId="4" pageNumber="397" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="4.[173,1407,478,884]" pageId="4" pageNumber="397">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[174,421,479,502]" pageId="4" pageNumber="397">EMMENDED DIAGNOSIS</emphasis>
— Clypeus with protruding median lobe. Palpal formula 6:3. Mesonotum with notauli and parapsidal furrows. Scutellum with scutellar groove. Forewing with three closed cells, narrow costal cell, median cell triangular and longer than rectangular submedian cell, latter at most half as long as former; prostigma inconspicuous and radial vein absent. Metapectal-propodeal complex finely areolate-rugulose. Mesopleuron without upper and lower foveae. Prosternum small. Female. Antenna monofiliform. Metasomal sternite IV extremely modified, with paired lateroventral fin-shaped projections. Occipital carina absent. Pronotal disc with median groove narrow and deep, only subtegular fovea present or conspicuous (
<figureCitation box="[602,688,686,711]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[204,260,1739,1759]" captionText="FIGURE 2 Female holotype of Galodoxa torquata from Philippines; a, lateral habitus; b-d, head in dorsal (b), lateral (c) and anterior (d) views; e-f, mesosoma in lateral (e) and dorsal (f) views; g, forewing; h, metasomal modifications in ventral view. Scale bars:a,1 mm; b, e, g, 500 µm; c, d, h, 200 µm." pageId="4" pageNumber="397">Figure 2</figureCitation>
). Male. Antenna at least as long as thorax (
<figureCitation box="[1130,1238,686,711]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[204,260,1738,1758]" captionText="FIGURE 3 Male of Galodoxatorquata from Laos (left) and Papua New Guinea (right);a-b, lateral habitus;c-d, head in dorsal view;e-f, head in lateral view;g-h, mesosoma in dorsal view.Scale bars:c-h,200 µm; a-b, 500 µm." pageId="4" pageNumber="397">Figures 3a</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1248,1290,686,711]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="9.[205,261,1738,1758]" captionText="FIGURE 4 Male of Galodoxa torquata from Laos (left) and Papua New Guinea (right); a-b, mesosoma in dorsal view; c-d, forewing; e-f, antenna; g-h, mandible. Scale bars: a-f, 500 µm; g-h,200 µm." pageId="4" pageNumber="397">4e, f</figureCitation>
), proximal flagellomeres submonofiliform and distal ones filiform. Head posteriorly with complex of posterior gular and occipital carinae (
<figureCitation box="[264,393,756,780]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[204,260,1738,1758]" captionText="FIGURE 3 Male of Galodoxatorquata from Laos (left) and Papua New Guinea (right);a-b, lateral habitus;c-d, head in dorsal view;e-f, head in lateral view;g-h, mesosoma in dorsal view.Scale bars:c-h,200 µm; a-b, 500 µm." pageId="4" pageNumber="397">Figures 3e, f</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[404,430,756,780]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="11.[203,259,1739,1759]" captionTargetBox="[204,1437,1281,1708]" captionTargetId="figure-525@11.[591,1077,1282,1708]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 5 Male of Galodoxa torquata; a, head,occipital and gular carinae (Laos);b, propodeal disc sculpture (Laos,left;Papua New Guinea,right);c, metasomal second sternum paired spots (Papua New Guinea), see arrows.Scale bars:a,500 µm; b, 200 µm; c, 100 µm." pageId="4" pageNumber="397">5a</figureCitation>
). Eye as in 
<figureCitation box="[547,630,756,780]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[204,260,1738,1758]" captionText="FIGURE 3 Male of Galodoxatorquata from Laos (left) and Papua New Guinea (right);a-b, lateral habitus;c-d, head in dorsal view;e-f, head in lateral view;g-h, mesosoma in dorsal view.Scale bars:c-h,200 µm; a-b, 500 µm." pageId="4" pageNumber="397">Figure 3</figureCitation>
c-f. Pronotal disc with anterior margin sharp and with two anterior foveae (
<figureCitation box="[181,310,790,815]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="9.[205,261,1738,1758]" captionText="FIGURE 4 Male of Galodoxa torquata from Laos (left) and Papua New Guinea (right); a-b, mesosoma in dorsal view; c-d, forewing; e-f, antenna; g-h, mandible. Scale bars: a-f, 500 µm; g-h,200 µm." pageId="4" pageNumber="397">Figure 4a, b</figureCitation>
). Mesopleuron with prepectal depression. Metasomal sternite II with pair of rounded spots (
<figureCitation box="[1302,1402,790,814]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="11.[203,259,1739,1759]" captionTargetBox="[204,1437,1281,1708]" captionTargetId="figure-525@11.[591,1077,1282,1708]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 5 Male of Galodoxa torquata; a, head,occipital and gular carinae (Laos);b, propodeal disc sculpture (Laos,left;Papua New Guinea,right);c, metasomal second sternum paired spots (Papua New Guinea), see arrows.Scale bars:a,500 µm; b, 200 µm; c, 100 µm." pageId="4" pageNumber="397">Figure 5c</figureCitation>
, arrows). Genitalia with parameres completely divided, cuspis absent or inconspicuously developed and aedeagus shorter or longer than remaining structures (
<figureCitation box="[556,679,860,884]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="12.[876,932,1052,1072]" captionTargetBox="[878,1384,223,1009]" captionTargetId="figure-535@12.[822,1417,189,1009]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 6 Male genitalia; a, specimen from Laos (ventral view). b, specimen from Papua New Guinea (dorsal view). Scale bar: 75 µm." pageId="4" pageNumber="397">Figure 6a, b</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
